Supertramp Dude (nguy1086@gmi.edu) wrote:

> I am currently running the WarpII Beta an DOS/Windows3.11 with a 486dx2-66
> and 8M of RAM.  Now if my understanding is correct,  OS/2 is a 32 bit
> operating system, right?  If so that means that data access from RAM can be
> done with a single call of a 32bit address.  So why is the Workplace shell
> so dam slow?

Because WPS is so dam extensive. Has nothing to do with 32-bit.
Get more RAM, and you'll be surprised. 8 MB is not enough to take
all swapping out of your system. WPS is no ProgMan. It is far more than that.

> Compare the shell with Windows Program manager. In Windows I
> must have over 40 program groups.  When I double click on a group, the
> contents are shown right away with no Hard drive access.

ProgMan is a menu. It loads icons and names. Nothing more. Of course
this is fast.

> On the other
> side, OS2 Workplace shell I only have about 10 folders and when I double
> click on a folder the Hard Drive goes crazy for awhile then the contents of
> the folder are shown, much slower!!

Folders are file system objects, not menus. OS/2 has to look them up
file by file.

> Even with mutiple opens to the same
> folder, OS2 still needs to access the HArd Drive?? Whats the deal hear?
> Where is my 1Meg disk cache at work. Does this cache really stink that bad?

It is probably not the DATA but other system stuff that's in the way.
You'll be better off decreasing the cache and thus increasing the working
RAM. OS/2 is no Windows. It actually uses your RAM.

> Why cant OS2 store all the contents of each folder into RAM like MS
> Windows?  This
> would make OS2 seem much faster, agreed? 

Yes, absolutely. It can do so (do not close a folder, but minimise
it or hide it. You'll see the difference). It also costs you performance
later on, when you want to run more programs at the same time.

> OS2 has HPFS which is suppose to be faster and "pre emptive multitasking"
> which is also suppose to be faster and protected mode execution which is
> suppose to make things stable, but if the shell is slower then Windows then
> most people will never really care about this other stuff.

RAM! RAM! RAM! RAM! Get more RAM! RAM is everything. Give the beast 16 meg
and it starts to scream.
Don't try to multitask in an environment that was meant to run one (1)
program (i.e. Windows). You need more RAM if you want to multitask.
Every biger system (no PC) has 16 or more megs of RAM. Sometimes even
64 or 128 meg. That's not for nothing.

And Win95 will have EXACTLY the same problem, so you want to get more
RAM anyway.

> Does anyone know of a faster shell then the Workplace shell, for OS2???

Yes, but they are ProgMan-like. Go out to ftp-os2.cdrom.com and enjoy.

